I came across a couple of big flaws in how render targets are managed in GraphicsDevice.

First if you look at this code...

```
var bindings = new RenderTargetBinding[1];

bindings[0] = new RenderTargetBinding(target1);
device.SetRenderTargets(bindings);
DrawToTarget();

bindings[0] = new RenderTargetBinding(target2);
device.SetRenderTargets(bindings);
DrawToTarget();
```

This code doesn't work...  `target2` is never written to.  This is because internally GraphicsDevice keeps ahold of the RenderTargetBinding array we passed to it.  This means when we set it the second time the arrays are already equal... we then early out without changing the render target.

The second bug was this...

```
device.SetRenderTarget(target1);
var bindings = device.GetRenderTargets();
bindings[0] = new RenderTargetBinding(target2);
device.SetRenderTargets(bindings);
DrawToTarget();
```

Like the code above... `target2` is not rendered to.  This is because `GetRenderTargets()` returns the internal `_currentRenderTargetBindings` array...  which then we modify.  Again when we call `SetRenderTargets` the arrays are equal in value and no render target change occurs.

To solve this i made the following changes...
- _currentRenderTargetBindings is a fixed sized array and never null.
- Added _currentRenderTargetCount to keep track of the count of bound render targets. 
- GetRenderTargets() now returns copy of the bindings array.
- ApplyRenderTargets() now copies the incoming binding array elements.

I know there have been other render target bugs reported lately...  not sure if my changes here resolve some of them as well.

There is a problem with:

```
System.IndexOutOfRangeException: Array index is out of range.
```

in class

```
SamplerStateCollection.cs
```

when trying to set property

```
public SamplerState this [int index] 
     {
         get 
            { 
                return _samplers[index]; 
            }

         set 
            {
                if (_samplers[index] == value)
                    return;

                _samplers[index] = value;

#if DIRECTX
                _d3dDirty |= 1 << index;
#endif
            }
      }
```

Problem occured only when using MonoGame together with Dynamic Particle System Framework on Android device. On emulator works fine. Device specification:

```
GPU: Mali 400
CPU: Boxchip A13
```

As a workaround I added simple 'if' statement, but I don't think this is the way it should be fixed :)

```
        public SamplerState this [int index] 
        {
            get 
            { 
                return _samplers[index]; 
            }

            set 
            {
                if (_samplers.Length > index)
                {
                    if (_samplers[index] == value)
                        return;

                    _samplers[index] = value;
                }

#if DIRECTX
                _d3dDirty |= 1 << index;
#endif
            }
        }
```

On Windows 8 RT (Metro) there is a problem with rendering sprites from SpriteBatch and using custom shaders with them.

I'm trying to use simple shader changing texture to grayscale:

``` HLSL
sampler TextureSampler : register(s0);


float4 PixelShaderFunction(float4 color : COLOR0, float2 texCoord : TEXCOORD0) : COLOR0
{
    float4 tex = tex2D(TextureSampler, texCoord);
    tex.rgb = dot(tex.rgb, float3(0.3, 0.59, 0.11));
    return tex;
}


technique Technique1
{
    pass Pass1
    {
        PixelShader = compile ps_4_0_level_9_1 PixelShaderFunction();
    }
}
```

Rendering with such effect produces wrong image (examples below). I'm rendering them using such code:

``` C#

//in draw method

_spriteBatch.Begin(SpriteSortMode.Immediate, BlendState.AlphaBlend);
_effectSprite.CurrentTechnique.Passes[0].Apply();
_spriteBatch.Draw(_tex2d, new Vector2(0, 0), Color.White);
_spriteBatch.End();
```

I've created a test project that presents this bug - it allows to render sprite without any shaders, with a shader, and using similar shader file, and by drawing texture on quad, using DrawUserIndexedPrimitives method.

I've tested it on my Geforce 9600GT (Supports 10.0, 9.3, 9.2, 9.1 feature levels) and on Intel HD 3000 (supports the same as GeForce and 10.1), and result is:

